(9 comments)'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2018-12-20 20:39:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

(12 comments)

Thanks Mel and Kevin for weighing in and reviewing this. Replies inline. I don't have a drawing board in my home office, but I have lots of loose leaf paper so I'll start thinking about how to avoid re-using (and hacking) the shelve/unshelve code and what new compute methods would look like, then probably start coding up an alternative PoC as soon as I decouple the existing big change so the compute/conductor/API parts are split apart. I can't say I'll have an alternative PoC done in time for the spec freeze, however, so it might mean needing to make the spec a bit more generic (fewer low-level implementation details and more of just a high level flow)."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2018-12-31 22:51:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I did spend today breaking apart some of the big PoC patch and sketching through what the flow would look like without shelve/unshelve, and it's actually going to be a lot of the same kind of stuff - essentially a hybrid of resize and shelve/unshelve without the disk transfer stuff because we still have to disconnect volumes and unplug vifs from the source host before we connect/plug vifs on the dest host, and that includes dealing with volume attachments and port bindings. The main benefit I see so far is decoupling from the shelve methods so those don't become dual purpose and so the instance is still left on the source host (so we don't have to reschedule on revert), but the downside is it's going to be a lot of new and mostly duplicated code, but maybe that's OK/preferable. I don't have the compute changes written up yet though."}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2019-01-02 13:30:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I've read this. I don't reckon I have sufficient conductor or "operational" experience to make an effective judgement but this reads as an accurate reflection of accomplishing this task within nova, modulo expressed concern that leveraging shelve may not be appropriate.

If I understand correctly the gist of what is happening here is the following steps managed with nova itself, using an established set of api calls:

* save the state of a server and kill it
* bring that state back up in a different cell, probably  at a different size

The gravy being provided by nova is that you can confirm or deny the results, and revert back to the old state if unhappy.

During (some of? the whole time?) this change the workload is interrupted.

So is the main value here the "established set of api calls" and the "gravy"?

For sake of inquiry: If the workload is getting interrupted anyway, is it worth the added complexity in nova when something else could potentially do the orchestration?

I assume that debate has already been had, and the existence of the POC is the result of saying "this is worth exploring, let's try it and see"?'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2019-01-02 14:14:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Chris, something could technically handle the orchestration external to nova, but that would be really complicated given all the moving parts (DB surgery including knowing which tables you have to move, it's not just the instances table), status updates and copying history to the other cell, scheduling and allocations, and dealing with external resources like ports and volumes which have to be dealt with at the host layer. The workload is interrupted yes, but it is during cold migration / resize today as well. One of the main benefits of cells v2 is that we can orchestrate operations like this "from the top" which is something we couldn't do well with cells v1, so being able to abstract this type of move operation across cells within nova is worthwhile if it can be pulled off in a sane way (I might go bald in the process).'}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2019-01-02 14:25:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

> Chris, something could technically handle the orchestration
 > external to nova, but that would be really complicated given all
 > the moving parts (DB surgery including knowing which tables you
 > have to move, it's not just the instances table), status updates
 > and copying history to the other cell, scheduling and allocations,
 > and dealing with external resources like ports and volumes which
 > have to be dealt with at the host layer. The workload is
 > interrupted yes, but it is during cold migration / resize today as
 > well. One of the main benefits of cells v2 is that we can
 > orchestrate operations like this "from the top" which is something
 > we couldn't do well with cells v1, so being able to abstract this
 > type of move operation across cells within nova is worthwhile if it
 > can be pulled off in a sane way (I might go bald in the process).

Thanks for the quick response. I was asking about external orchestration, I wasn't really suggesting we not do it, more trying to understand the decision process. However, what I meant appears to be a bit different than what you've read (so I don't explain myself well enough). I basically meant: don't do any of "DB surgery including knowing which tables you have to move, it's not just the instances table), status updates and copying history to the other cell, scheduling and allocations, and dealing with external resources like ports and volumes which have to be dealt with at the host layer."

Instead (from a client):

* snapshot
* build new "over there", attaching ports and volumes as required
* destroy the old one

(losing history, uuids, etc, so I guess that's why not, but...)

I suppose this sort of thing is at the heart of "what is nova, anyway?"'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2019-01-02 16:47:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2019-01-02 16:57:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Chris, yeah you've described what I have in the alternative section, and is what operators have had to do for a long time to move data across sites/regions, e.g. I have Havana installed at site A and rather than go through the trouble of upgrading that to Rocky, I just stand up Rocky at site B and do the snapshot dance. That's painful for ops since there is no common solution for it, and it's painful for users who have things written against specific IPs, UUIDs, etc (granted they shouldn't do that, but people love their pets)."}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2019-01-02 17:32:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Improve the documentation for skydive

The documentation has been added to, which should make the deployment
of skydive easier to understand. Additionally an overlay inventory
and examples have been provided showing how skydive can be deployed
as part of an OSA cloud without having to extend or otherwise modify
the openstack-ansible inventory/configuration.

Change-Id: Iccc0d23fa8a6047d1bcae53614c38e5ea0945f82
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin@cloudnull.com>

[{'created': '2018-06-15 13:26:13.000000000', 'message': 'Improve patching of sys.argv

More in-depth type checking of args in Python 3.6 causes issues
with the current approach to patching sys.argv for agent unit
tests;  Directly patch argv with the required test arguments
rather than using return_value (which does not really do what
the test assumes it does).

Change-Id: I8966323e3f0853351fe27207ae63901c2f9f351a
'}]
commit_message:
Improve patching of sys.argv

More in-depth type checking of args in Python 3.6 causes issues
with the current approach to patching sys.argv for agent unit
tests;  Directly patch argv with the required test arguments
rather than using return_value (which does not really do what
the test assumes it does).

Change-Id: I8966323e3f0853351fe27207ae63901c2f9f351a

[{'created': '2019-01-09 15:55:50.000000000', 'message': 'Adjust ssh timeouts

Generic driver jobs are failing because of timeouts when
establishing the initial ssh connection from manila-share
to the service VM.

Bump up the default value of the connection timeout for paramiko
client and also set the banner timeout since the failure occurred
during banner exchange.  Set the two timeouts to the same value
for now.  This ensures that the connection timeout is at least as
long as the banner timeout and there is no current need in manila
to control these independently.

This is more of a workaround than a real fix since a real fix
would remove the delay during banner exchange.  I suspect that
the real fix will need to be in neutron/ovs though.

commit_message:
Adjust ssh timeouts

Generic driver jobs are failing because of timeouts when
establishing the initial ssh connection from manila-share
to the service VM.

Bump up the default value of the connection timeout for paramiko
client and also set the banner timeout since the failure occurred
during banner exchange.  Set the two timeouts to the same value
for now.  This ensures that the connection timeout is at least as
long as the banner timeout and there is no current need in manila
to control these independently.

This is more of a workaround than a real fix since a real fix
would remove the delay during banner exchange.  I suspect that
the real fix will need to be in neutron/ovs though.

Change-Id: Ib5e59faaf9667b9cb5e7d4072531b7d6c3d4da39
Partial-bug: #1807216
(cherry picked from commit 7548706b0928f2c23bf27e10d116ceca585660e4)
(cherry picked from commit 8919db0186f8da9f2f492d80c8a3700c3d9367d1)
(cherry picked from commit 2abde73d1e4a91569b2c844632acc10676b11e26)

commit_message:
Fix defaults for ConfigParser

As of 3.7, the configparser module will not allow defaults values to be None.
This patch replaces such values with "default".

Change-Id: Id5a414412cd66d479fb8f8784cba5deddc628dfd
Closes-Bug: #1785641

commit_message:
Set paramiko logging to DEBUG level

Connections to backends via paramiko often fail for obscure
reasons.

If the service log level is DEBUG, increase paramiko logging
to DEBUG level as well so that we have more information when issues
of this sort occur.

Change-Id: I44d8902d58c2ad48b8a37dfbff96c5b9471651e4
(cherry picked from commit 575d6ae62140681b0be6ef2eccec5b3664524a6d)

revisions:
[{'created': '2018-12-10 10:49:27.000000000', 'message': "Adding ansible-runner to global-requirements

networking-ansible ML2 driver invokes ansible via an ASL 2.0 python
wrapper named ansible-runner.

Is the library actively maintained?
Yes - https://github.com/ansible/ansible-runner
I've been working with the maintainers and they've been very responsive

Is the library good code?
Yes - Documentation has been good and contributing has been easy
stability has been good and good coding practices appear to be
practiced.

Is the library python 3 compatible?
Yes
https://github.com/ansible/ansible-runner/commit/b86c50978e70526e952a1a19bc94997f99b98992

Is the library license compatible?
Yes - ASL 2.0

Is the library already packaged in the distros we target (Ubuntu latest / Fedora latest)?
Fedora - Yes
Ubuntu - No

Is the function of this library already covered by other libraries in global-requirements.txt?
I don't believe so. Afaik it's the only distibuted lib that provides a
programatic interface to ansible.

Is the library required for OpenStack project or related dev or infrastructure setup? (Answer to this should be Yes, of course) Which?
Yes - networking-ansible invokes it directly to manage switching
infrastructure via Ansible Networking

Reason for this backport:
We want to support networking-ansible in the Queens release. ansible-runner
is used only by networking-ansible so we won't affect other projects with
this patch. With ansible-runner not being present in Queens we won't be
able to make networking-ansible working in the Queens release.

Conflicts:
	global-requirements.txt
	lower-constraints.txt
	upper-constraints.txt

Change-Id: I33725dbb61f0e6423ef358602822e2e6bcef4abd
(cherry picked from commit a449abac5d3336db765006d8cc6829fd4785dccb)

commit_message:
Adding ansible-runner to global-requirements

networking-ansible ML2 driver invokes ansible via an ASL 2.0 python
wrapper named ansible-runner.

Is the library actively maintained?
Yes - https://github.com/ansible/ansible-runner
I've been working with the maintainers and they've been very responsive

Is the library good code?
Yes - Documentation has been good and contributing has been easy
stability has been good and good coding practices appear to be
practiced.

Is the library python 3 compatible?
Yes
https://github.com/ansible/ansible-runner/commit/b86c50978e70526e952a1a19bc94997f99b98992

Is the library license compatible?
Yes - ASL 2.0

Is the library already packaged in the distros we target (Ubuntu latest / Fedora latest)?
Fedora - Yes
Ubuntu - No

Is the function of this library already covered by other libraries in global-requirements.txt?
I don't believe so. Afaik it's the only distibuted lib that provides a
programatic interface to ansible.

Is the library required for OpenStack project or related dev or infrastructure setup? (Answer to this should be Yes, of course) Which?
Yes - networking-ansible invokes it directly to manage switching
infrastructure via Ansible Networking

Reason for this backport:
We want to support networking-ansible in the Queens release. ansible-runner
is used only by networking-ansible so we won't affect other projects with
this patch. With ansible-runner not being present in Queens we won't be
able to make networking-ansible working in the Queens release.

pexpect library also had to be bumped because ansible-runner has a
requirement on it given as >= 4.5

Conflicts:

commit_message:
Added Recursive DNS relation

Once BIND is enabled for recursion, it is possible
to configure neutron gateway's and ovs's dnsmasq
automatically by relating BIND charm with ovs or
gateway

Change-Id: I0537222b2a03a5e9648813a2abf494eda47bbd46
Partial-Bug: #1773377

While looking into this, I noticed that no one else (well, I only looked at Cinder, Nova, and Keystone) has a Debian install guide.  I wonder if we should delete it?'}, {'account_id': 11904, 'date': '2018-08-22 14:27:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

FWIW, I'm pushing back on this change elsewhere (and I think someone else has already proposed it for Glance). We don't declare anywhere I've seen that this should be run from a root shell and the change in the prompt character is not obvious enough to let readers know to do that.

Also, depending on how the database has been set up, just being in a root shell may not be enough for this to work. IMO, it's better to keep it the older explicit way."}, {'account_id': 11904, 'date': '2018-08-22 14:27:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

And yeah, we can probably drop the debian guide.'}, {'account_id': 5202, 'date': '2019-01-15 11:29:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1'}]

commit_message:
Functional: DB Failures workaround

Lower the concurrency of the functional tests to 1. A FIXME was left in
the code so the workaround can be removed upon properly fixing the bug.

We need this workaround for now because the gate is taking forever to
merge other patches due to this problem, many rechecks are needed wasting
gate resource and time.

Change-Id: Ia51351c4245c400a44a2924468cf79866defbc18
Partial-Bug: #1808146
Signed-off-by: Lucas Alvares Gomes <lucasagomes@gmail.com>

pylint: Drop non-existing IPAddressField

horizon/forms/__init__.py exposed IPAddressField via __all__,
but IPAddressField does not exist in Django code.
It addresses pylint undefined-all-variable error.

commit_message:
Remove -U from pip install

'pip install -U' ugrades specified packages, this is not necessary
since we use constraints, remove the parameter '-U' from the line.

Change-Id: I2582c1a1995bb4cf903d4ce2e1ebb3fca930ea01

This change is missing the needed-by to the governance change."}, {'account_id': 24162, 'date': '2019-01-03 14:24:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 24162, 'date': '2019-01-03 14:24:09.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 11.'}, {'account_id': 6928, 'date': '2019-01-03 15:09:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11:

(1 comment)

I'm starting to think we just want to cut the stable branch on github and merge 2.0-dev back to master before we do the import. Otherwise we end up with a bunch of busy work on Gerrit that just duplicates what is already there (or we import the feature branch and make busy work for the Gerrit admins).

That might delay this import a bit as we would need to cut the stable/1.0 branch, make sure consumers have a chance to switch to using it, then merge 2.0-dev back to master and make master 2.0. I think it's the cleanest option though.

The other thing we _could_ do, but I suspect isn't supported by the import process, is to import 2.0-dev as the Gerrit master, and the Github master as stable/1.0. That way when people migrate to the Gerrit version they can select the appropriate branch and there's no chance of accidentally breaking someone. I'm guessing the import process isn't sophisticated enough to support mapping branches that way though."}, {'account_id': 10969, 'date': '2019-01-04 15:20:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 4146, 'date': '2019-01-10 23:39:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2019-01-11 07:46:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11: Workflow-1

Ben, Sorin, Is this ready to merge or should it have a Workflow -1?

Do you have a change up for governance repo to add this to tripleo?

I'm also waiting for PTL +1 - thus marking as WIP."}, {'account_id': 24162, 'date': '2019-01-14 12:50:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

Ben, can you confirm if this is ready with a a vote?

I am looking at https://github.com/cybertron/openstack-virtual-baremetal/branches and I see 4 branches instead of two.

I guess you still need to archive "2.0-dev" and "routed-networks" before giving the go (so we avoid importing them).'}, {'account_id': 6928, 'date': '2019-01-14 14:26:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Code-Review+1

Yeah, I was still cleaning up the branches and verifying that everything worked before import. Turns out TripleO broke the OVB nic-configs again so I got delayed fixing that.

Everything is good to go now though. Only master and stable/1.0 branches exist and my last test passed.'}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2019-01-14 15:28:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

Thanks, Ben. Still waiting for Tripleo PTL to +1...'}, {'account_id': 10873, 'date': '2019-01-15 10:20:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2019-01-15 10:51:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1'}]

[{'created': '2018-11-16 07:58:27.000000000', 'message': 'Fixing race condition and fix discrepency when reusing Events

Is there a race condition on the wait method, a greenthread A is blocked
on the wait, but another greenthread B calls clear() and
then set(), B calls self._event.send(), but A is waiting on a different
eventlet Event which is no longer used by the oslo.service Event...

Also the threading.Event object allows calling set() multiple times, but
the eventlet.Event object only permits send() to be called once,
before a reset() is required to reuse the Event.

Calling eventletutils.Event.set() multiple times triggers an
AssertionError from eventlet.Event.  This change resets the underlying
eventlet.Event if the set() method had already been called previously,
and ensures the eventletutils.Event behaves the same as the
threading.Event.

Change-Id: I726be277d6f8a8f8b455d9d5de59ff05b8349ad9

commit_message:
Fixing race condition and fix discrepency when reusing Events

Is there a race condition on the wait method, a greenthread A is blocked
on the wait, but another greenthread B calls clear() and
then set(), B calls self._event.send(), but A is waiting on a different
eventlet Event which is no longer used by the oslo.service Event...

Also the threading.Event object allows calling set() multiple times, but
the eventlet.Event object only permits send() to be called once,
before a reset() is required to reuse the Event.

Calling eventletutils.Event.set() multiple times triggers an
AssertionError from eventlet.Event. This change resets the underlying eventlet.Event
if the set() method had already been called previously, and ensures the eventletutils.Event
behaves the same as the threading.Event.

Change-Id: I726be277d6f8a8f8b455d9d5de59ff05b8349ad9

[{'created': '2017-10-06 16:00:30.000000000', 'message': 'Add retries to LVM logical volume activation

We are running into failures activating snapshots where the syslog shows
the output "thin: Unable to activate thin device while pool is suspended"
when attempting to use quickly after creation. This appears to be a race
where there are still internal things being done after the snapshot is
created.

This is a bit of a punt, but with local testing the thin pool state either
does not visibily change or transitions so fast that it is hard to capture
the state transition in the vgdisplay. Since we know this operations works
most of the time, it would seem we are just giving up before the pool gets
back into the right state to do this activation.

Rather than trying to get the thin pool state and parse the output of the
command, just adding retries to the operation that back off between each
attempt. Based on what we've seen with successful runs, this should allow
it to fail while the pool is in this transitional state and attempt again
later when hopefully things have settled.

Change-Id: I3e7037b3571665251db8dee2cf22cab1297106c9
Closes-bug: #1642111
'}]
commit_message:
Add retries to LVM logical volume activation

We are running into failures activating snapshots where the syslog shows
the output "thin: Unable to activate thin device while pool is suspended"
when attempting to use quickly after creation. This appears to be a race
where there are still internal things being done after the snapshot is
created.

This is a bit of a punt, but with local testing the thin pool state either
does not visibily change or transitions so fast that it is hard to capture
the state transition in the vgdisplay. Since we know this operations works
most of the time, it would seem we are just giving up before the pool gets
back into the right state to do this activation.

Rather than trying to get the thin pool state and parse the output of the
command, just adding retries to the operation that back off between each
attempt. Based on what we've seen with successful runs, this should allow
it to fail while the pool is in this transitional state and attempt again
later when hopefully things have settled.

Change-Id: I3e7037b3571665251db8dee2cf22cab1297106c9
Closes-bug: #1642111

commit_message:
Use existing (but not indexed) interface

The send_storage_backend_data method was written before I realised
that a cinder-backend interface already existed. This change
updates send_storage_backend_data to use the existing interface
which has a slightly different method name and signature for
sending relation data to principle.

Change-Id: I6eeedffe2961e97f8ea04ad85be5f9aa9b8820ed

commit_message:
Add VNF to monitor after restarting tacker service

If you restart tacker service, it doesn't monitor previously
created VNFs.

This patch will read all VNFs from db and add to monitor
during initialization of VFNM plugin.

Change-Id: I1d49f9442dbc34794e01fbefb4ef82af21171956
Closes-Bug: #1616712

[Unity] Add `force detach` support

Add support to force detach a volume from all hosts on Unity.

commit_message:
Update only python-tripleoclient before uc upgrade.

As the python-tripleoclient requires the tripleo-heat-templates
and tripleo-common packages in its distgit requirements [0],
there is no need to update them specifically. They will be also
updated when updating python-tripleoclient.

[0] - https://github.com/rdo-packages/tripleoclient-distgit/blob/rpm-master/python-tripleoclient.spec#L138
[1] - https://github.com/rdo-packages/tripleoclient-distgit/blob/rpm-master/python-tripleoclient.spec#L104

Change-Id: If08798d8dbf2cd2bbc7de4865d6a68e73bd79553

commit_message:
Add floating IP filter to floating IP list command

Add a parameter ``--floating-ip-address`` to ``floating ip list``
because it's supported by the API and also more efficient than the
current ``floating ip show``. This also works as a work-around for
pagination issues ``floating ip show`` might run into with an IP
parameter.

Change-Id: I113e3fa2495e1e86bb553c55c44f71a3f9f49d23

commit_message:
Update coverage environment and use template for cover

After switch to using stestr, testrepository is unnecessary
and it is removed in patch[1]. After patch[1] got merged
tox -e cover returns "error: option --coverage not recognized".

In this patch fixed coverage environment to default stestr setup.
Also used openstack-tox-cover template, this runs the cover job
in the check queue only.

[1]: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/581686/
Closes-Bug: #1809230

Change-Id: I77a295a64e2c4d128a6772e400c0968f40d11c1d

commit_message:
Uninstall policy.json from openstack_dashboard correctly

During uninstalling masakari using devstack, it fails to remove
policy.json.
This patch fixes this issue by pointing to the correct path of
the policy.json file.

Change-Id: I1b9c009fe4d4305f9b7992c0c46a65ba0bac61a8

commit_message:
Correct Subnet Object filter value by segment_id
     * currently IPAM cannot filter subnet Object by segment_id
     * correcectly. this path is to fix the bug
     * refer to https://bugs.launchpad.net/tricircle/+bug/1810314
     * as get_values method in _model_query.py mostly return 
     * sqlalchemy.util._collections.result object but sometimes will 
     * return dict object such as FakeQuery in Other Project Unitests 
 
Change-Id: I88d8f029be2f2f28fc2c963e88ee05f05e7a9aad

commit_message:
Update FakeQuery get results fileterered by table
fields to fix keyerror bug 1810314.

1. What is the problem?

right now Tricircle Unitests FakeQuery cannot get results
filtered by table fields get_value method in
/neutron/db/_model_query.py updated.

2. What is the solution to the problem?
update FakeQuery method add filtered fields function

Change-Id: Id51684ab840ad999b16fa417f7985e5c4a353367
Signed-off-by: zhangchi <zhangchi@szzt.com.cn>
Co-Authored-By: tangzhuo <ztang@hnu.edu.cn>

commit_message:
Fail node cleaning on timeout

The Use of a retry with continue-on causes the task
wait_for_provision_state to finish in success. We need another
task to test the provisioning state and conditionally fail
based on that.

Closes-Bug: #1796293
Change-Id: I94fe438a05c3d20b927f9fe1bc8cc3ea10d85f1e
(cherry picked from commit 70ed6378186dca5735f7ff8f51190de7eb7bf3ca)

commit_message:
Workaround for failing gates

Work with 389-ds-base-1.4.0.20.  Following
https://pagure.io/389-ds-base/c/4fd73c5 `dscreate fromfile`
got renamed to `dscreate from-file`.

Save dogtag server files for future debug.

Removed pip install of dogtag-pki which installed old Dogtag client code.

Temporarily skipping paging tests and making grenade non-voting.

Change-Id: I4bbc3d39c8d4a3591374e5c4a733a987f001a896

commit_message:
Add VNF to monitor after restarting tacker service

If you restart tacker service, it doesn't monitor previously
created VNFs.

This patch will read all VNFs from db and add to monitor
during initialization of VFNM plugin.

Change-Id: I1d49f9442dbc34794e01fbefb4ef82af21171956
Closes-Bug: #1616712

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
and resubmit a new change-set.

Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
Workflow: https://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/developers.html

commit_message:
py3: object server

This does not do anything about replicator or other daemons,
only ports the server.

- wsgi_to_bytes(something.get('X-Foo')) assumes that None is possible
- Dunno if del-in-for-in-dict calls for clone or list(), using list()
- Fixed the zero-copy with EventletPlungerString(bytes)
- Yet another reminder that Request.blank() takes a WSGI string path

Curiously enough, the sleep(0) before checking for logging was
already present in the tests. The py3 scheduling merely forces us
to do it consistently throughout.

Change-Id: I203a54fddddbd4352be0e6ea476a628e3f747dc1

At the moment the 'OS::TripleO::Services::Timesync' service is
synonymous to 'OS::TripleO::Services::Ntp'. Let's use the more generic
Timesync service to pick up the new default in the event the value for
'OS::TripleO::Services::Timesync' changes.

Change-Id: I10704670ea57902add783e2473eeeaa72bf5eacf

commit_message:
Use Timesync service instead of Ntp

At the moment the 'OS::TripleO::Services::Timesync' service is
synonymous to 'OS::TripleO::Services::Ntp'. Let's use the more generic
Timesync service to pick up the new default in the event the value for
'OS::TripleO::Services::Timesync' changes.

Change-Id: I10704670ea57902add783e2473eeeaa72bf5eacf

commit_message:
Add YAML format into docs for policy file

kolla-ansible support yaml format for policy file[1] too, but the
docs missing it, this ps to add it.

[1]: https://github.com/openstack/kolla-ansible/blob/master/ansible/group_vars/all.yml#L393

commit_message:
Delete related encryption provider when a volume type is deleting

Currently volume_type_destroy() in api.py does not delete related
encryption provider (if it exists). As a result, 'encryption' table
accumulates orphaned records.
This patch fixes to delete related encryption provider when
a volume type is deleting.

Change-Id: I90962108ced5043d74b7a7984196b14b2a13eeab
Closes-Bug: 1797640

[{'created': '2018-12-25 12:14:16.000000000', 'message': "Don't modify global variables in unit tests

The unit test
test_enable_dhcp_helper_enable_metadata_nonisolated_dist_network
modifies the global variables fake_port1, fake_port2, creating flakiness
on unit tests that use those variables when execured in environments
with high concurrency.

Creating a deepcopy of the variable avoid that those changes can be
propagated to other unit tests.

Closes-Bug: #1809643

Change-Id: Idfd0e99739952baf4d7b545b406cd1b251deb5f8
Signed-off-by: aojeagarcia <aojeagarcia@suse.com>
(cherry picked from commit e83e5618b7ca71fb96bf460922480b9808b431b6)
"}]
commit_message:
Don't modify global variables in unit tests

The unit test
test_enable_dhcp_helper_enable_metadata_nonisolated_dist_network
modifies the global variables fake_port1, fake_port2, creating flakiness
on unit tests that use those variables when execured in environments
with high concurrency.

Creating a deepcopy of the variable avoid that those changes can be
propagated to other unit tests.

Closes-Bug: #1809643

Change-Id: Idfd0e99739952baf4d7b545b406cd1b251deb5f8
Signed-off-by: aojeagarcia <aojeagarcia@suse.com>
(cherry picked from commit e83e5618b7ca71fb96bf460922480b9808b431b6)

commit_message:
doc: Fix unnecessary spaces in folder paths

There are useless spaces in folder paths in https://docs.openstack.org/horizon/latest/configuration/customizing.html
This problem is caused by rst max line length.

Change-Id: Ie2b8e7178ceea98d8a78a2a8ba264cfa396324a7

subject: [Workaround] Determine nova.host from Prometheus instance
messages:
[{'account_id': 22406, 'date': '2019-01-10 04:43:56.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 22406, 'date': '2019-01-10 05:41:58.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2: Commit message was updated.'}, {'account_id': 26339, 'date': '2019-01-10 10:09:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 22406, 'date': '2019-01-11 07:38:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

> (2 comments)

Hi,

nova.services.list will return instance of novaclient.base.ListWithMeta.

> nova_host = nova_client.services.list(binary='nova-compute', host='exist-compute-host')
[<Service: 93>]
> nova_host.x_openstack_request_ids[0]
req-e60f7aa5-e3c8-425a-a673-39a580741a78

* It returns a ListWithMeta which contains 1 element: [<Service: 93>].

> nova_client.services.list(binary='nova-compute', host='non-exist-compute-host')
[]
> nova_host.x_openstack_request_ids[0]
req-e60f7aa5-e3c8-425a-a673-39a580741a78

* You can see that x_openstack_request_ids always exists. So I think checking if len(nova_host) > 0 like i do (if nova_host) is correct.

Regarding a generic solution, I think you're right but IMO, the spec will require several patchsets to be implemented, I guess. We can land  this patch like a workaround till the spec be completely implemented."}, {'account_id': 22406, 'date': '2019-01-11 07:38:43.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 22406, 'date': '2019-01-13 09:47:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Patch Set 3 was rebased'}, {'account_id': 22406, 'date': '2019-01-14 03:15:55.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 22406, 'date': '2019-01-14 03:17:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 26339, 'date': '2019-01-14 11:24:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

Since the more generic change will merge very soon, there is no use in his change. 
I added you as a reviewer, I'll appreciate it if you review it.
Thanks a lot for your help!"}, {'account_id': 22406, 'date': '2019-01-15 03:04:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

> Since the more generic change will merge very soon, there is no use
 > in his change.
 > I added you as a reviewer, I'll appreciate it if you review it.
 > Thanks a lot for your help!

I see, let me check it. About this patch, I abandon it now"}, {'account_id': 22406, 'date': '2019-01-15 03:05:04.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

We have a generic solution now [1].

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/630514/'}]

commit_message:
[Workaround] Determine nova.host from Prometheus instance

Nova.host usually returns hostname instead of ip address.
If Prometheus instance is ip address, Vitrage may not determine
relationship between Nova.host and Prometheus alert.

Change-Id: I8159362fe78a04dcdae38fc561151a7793c5d0c0

commit_message:
Multi-region support in shared Keystone service deployment

Currently, Horizon does not support login with specified region in
shared-keystone, multi-region deployment, the existing
AVAILABLE_REGIONS only works with multi-keystone, multi-region
environment. This patch provides end user the ability to select
region when log in Horizon. A new setting called
'OPENSTACK_KEYSTONE_REGION_CHOICES' is introduced in Horizon config
file (in a following patch). The 'AVAILABLE_REGIONS' setting takes
precedence over 'OPENSTACK_KEYSTONE_REGION_CHOICES'.

Implements: blueprint horizon-multi-region-support
Change-Id: If02810039c841ea6d9ff80f808db1976d6e907d1

[{'created': '2019-01-03 19:42:34.000000000', 'message': "Use eventlet.patcher.original to get Python select module in get_hub

get_hub function was added in commit b155da42 with the idea to bypass
eventlet automatic hub selection that prefers epoll if available by default.

Since version 0.20.0 eventlet removed select.poll() function in its patched
select module (eventlet.green.select), see:
   - https://github.com/eventlet/eventlet/commit/614a20462

So if eventlet monkey patching is done before a get_hub() call (as now in
wsgi.py since commit c9410c7d) if we use 'import select' we get the eventlet

To prevent that we use eventlet.patcher.original function to get python select
module to test if poll() is available on current platform.

Closes-Bug: 1804627
(cherry picked from commit 4809884d9f20eb0be6df9840e4e6a75577fecc4c)

commit_message:
Use eventlet.patcher.original to get Python select module in get_hub

get_hub function was added in commit b155da42 with the idea to bypass
eventlet automatic hub selection that prefers epoll if available by default.

Since version 0.20.0 eventlet removed select.poll() function in its patched
select module (eventlet.green.select), see:
   - https://github.com/eventlet/eventlet/commit/614a20462

So if eventlet monkey patching is done before a get_hub() call (as now in
wsgi.py since commit c9410c7d) if we use 'import select' we get the eventlet
version that don't have poll attribute.

To prevent that we use eventlet.patcher.original function to get python select
module to test if poll() is available on current platform.

Change-Id: I69b3db3951b3d3b6583845978deb2883492e7f0f
Closes-Bug: 1804627
(cherry picked from commit 4809884d9f20eb0be6df9840e4e6a75577fecc4c)

commit_message:
Fix for CI information in SPDK volume driver

It was originally planned to create own independent CI
for SPDK driver, but finally it was created as a part
of Mellanox CI. Information in driver should be
updated accordingly.

Signed-off-by: Maciej Szwed <maciej.szwed@intel.com>
Change-Id: Idf7cebb4622d7d4d51d8ad9d0a45d73119d67d12

subject: SPDK drivers documentation

SPDK drivers documentation

This is an SPDK block storage configuration
documentation describing how to prepare and use
SPDK volume driver.

Signed-off-by: Maciej Szwed <maciej.szwed@intel.com>

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC

Adding SPDK volume driver

Adding Storage Performance Development Kit volume
driver. SPDK NVMe-oF Target driver depends on this
driver. It provides a new type of a backend.

Signed-off-by: Maciej Szwed <maciej.szwed@intel.com>

commit_message:
Don't modify global variables in unit tests

The unit test
test_enable_dhcp_helper_enable_metadata_nonisolated_dist_network
modifies the global variables fake_port1, fake_port2, creating flakiness
on unit tests that use those variables when execured in environments
with high concurrency.

Creating a deepcopy of the variable avoid that those changes can be
propagated to other unit tests.

Closes-Bug: #1809643

Change-Id: Idfd0e99739952baf4d7b545b406cd1b251deb5f8
Signed-off-by: aojeagarcia <aojeagarcia@suse.com>
(cherry picked from commit e83e5618b7ca71fb96bf460922480b9808b431b6)

commit_message:
Allow run metadata api per cell

Adds configuration option ``[api]/local_metadata_per_cell``
to allow user run Nova metadata API service per cell. Doing
this can avoid query API DB for instance information each
time an instance query for its metadata.

Implements blueprint run-meta-api-per-cell

Change-Id: I2e6ebb551e782e8aa0ac90169f4d4b8895311b3c

commit_message:
Initiating Cinder Volume Manager with large number of volumes

This patch adds the option to split retrieved volumes and snapshots
by chunks during Volume Manager host initialization. Query results
will be obtained in batches from the database and not in one shot
to avoid extreme memory usage. Max number of volumes and snapshots
per batch is controlled by option init_host_max_objects_retrieval.
Option is disabled by default for backward compatibility.

To migrate any ConfKeyManager keys based on fixed_key to the currently
configured key manager Volume Manager will use special lightweight
object - VolumeMigration.

Change-Id: I53eccc77fdc2c35b27ed430af62dc18e7d1bde69
Closes-Bug: 1681374

commit_message:
Add force to action_update

This patch adds the force query parameter to action_update.
When force is set to true on an action cancel request the
action status will be updated in the database to cancelled
rather than signaled to cancel. This will also update any
child actions to update their status in the database to
cancelled.

Change-Id: I45ab4a6ad57e3bfe791da1d2e70d3b2ed3ad9a21

commit_message:
Support for an additional PPA for Cinder plugins

Cinder storage plugins may involve vendor drivers which live
outside of the cinder tree. To support these add a default
install handler that checks for an additional source and adds it
if found.

[{'created': '2019-01-14 14:52:57.000000000', 'message': "Define types for C calls in netlink_lib

Previously this was not done, which meant all arguments were
assumed to be ints. As long as we didn't get any large pointer
addresses this worked fine, but for some reason the addition of
threading to oslo.privsep triggered larger addresses that were then
truncated. This caused segfaults in the underlying C library because
we were passing it invalid pointers.

This change sets argument and return types for all of the calls

c6d358d4c6926638fe9d5194e3da112c2750c6a4 in core neutron.

commit_message:
Define types for C calls in netlink_lib

Previously this was not done, which meant all arguments were
assumed to be ints. As long as we didn't get any large pointer
addresses this worked fine, but for some reason the addition of
threading to oslo.privsep triggered larger addresses that were then
truncated. This caused segfaults in the underlying C library because
we were passing it invalid pointers.

This change sets argument and return types for all of the calls
that are used in the module.

Note that this is the same change as
c6d358d4c6926638fe9d5194e3da112c2750c6a4 in core neutron.

Change-Id: Ic8d8b87e07b9c16970cb0f59b43a2d9fee79f018
Closes-Bug: 1811506

commit_message:
Remove tripleo newton and ocata jobs

Remove tripleo scenario00{1-7}-multinode-oooq.
Non-containerized multinode scenario jobs (1-7) are no longer
supported and should be removed from zuul config.

Rename tripleo scenario00{6,8,9}-multinode-oooq. These are
containerized scenario multinode jobs that were wrongly named.

Change-Id: I7e3bb3336e6dce1da68aaf0824c1bd5991a4ab61

subject: RHEL7 has updated libvirt to 4.5.x
messages:
[{'account_id': 12640, 'date': '2018-11-08 03:41:32.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 14288, 'date': '2018-11-08 07:40:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

ocata is kinda locked, without this being for security or major breakage reasons I can't see us merging this"}, {'account_id': 10343, 'date': '2018-11-08 12:21:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

> or major breakage reasons

Well... given the majority of deployments use libvirt, and Nova needs this to use libvirt, I'd call this major breakage for RHEL/Centos 7. :)

Anyway, isn't Ocata in extended maintenance now, meaning the rules are a bit more lax?"}, {'account_id': 6962, 'date': '2018-11-08 13:52:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 6962, 'date': '2018-11-08 14:20:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 14288, 'date': '2018-11-08 15:31:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

That makes sense, that, and the fact that libvirt-python is tied so closely to a non-python package makes it so that it'd be broken on rhel/cent without this patch."}, {'account_id': 11904, 'date': '2018-11-09 09:07:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Are there any concerns with using the newer version on platforms that have not updated libvirt like RHEL7? This is a pretty major bump (2.5 to 4.5) for an older stable branch.'}, {'account_id': 12898, 'date': '2018-11-23 05:43:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-2

(1 comment)

In the past we've strongly resisted doing this as it was next to impossible to find a version to update to that work on all the distros that support $branch.

Also before we could take this on Ocata we'd need to take it on all the previous branches to ensure we're following the extended maintenance policy and we don't force users to downgrade libvirt-python when they upgrade from ocata to pike or queens:

 Constraints
 -----------
 1.0.0-877-gcdf3ee6f   : libvirt-python===4.8.0
 origin/master         : libvirt-python===4.8.0
 origin/stable/rocky   : libvirt-python===4.4.0
 origin/stable/queens  : libvirt-python===3.10.0
 origin/stable/pike    : libvirt-python===3.10.0
 origin/stable/ocata   : libvirt-python===2.5.0
 origin/stable/newton  : libvirt-python===2.1.0"}, {'account_id': 14288, 'date': '2018-11-23 13:58:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: -Code-Review

/gentoo hat

we are packaging libvirt 4.5.0 and currently pike/queens and rocky are packaged

/reqs hat

tony, your right about updating the other branches before backporting all the way to ocata.  iirc stable policy allows for updates when things are broken, but I'm not sure about self-inflicted breakage like this."}, {'account_id': 14288, 'date': '2019-01-14 17:50:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

should we abandon this? iirc this issue was fixed in other reviews

https://github.com/openstack/requirements/blob/stable/ocata/upper-constraints.txt#L184'}, {'account_id': 12898, 'date': '2019-01-14 21:37:29.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

libvirt-python version should be greater than 4.5.x

commit_message:
Don't modify global variables in unit tests

The unit test
test_enable_dhcp_helper_enable_metadata_nonisolated_dist_network
modifies the global variables fake_port1, fake_port2, creating flakiness
on unit tests that use those variables when execured in environments
with high concurrency.

Creating a deepcopy of the variable avoid that those changes can be
propagated to other unit tests.

Closes-Bug: #1809643

Change-Id: Idfd0e99739952baf4d7b545b406cd1b251deb5f8
Signed-off-by: aojeagarcia <aojeagarcia@suse.com>
(cherry picked from commit e83e5618b7ca71fb96bf460922480b9808b431b6)

commit_message:
Restore nova-consoleauth to install docs

The installation of the nova-consoleauth service was erroneously
removed from the docs prematurely. The nova-consoleauth service
is still being used in Rocky, with the removal being possible in
Stein.

This should have been fixed as part of change
Ibbdc7c50c312da2acc59dfe64de95a519f87f123 but was missed.

This is also related to the release note update in Rocky
under change Ie637b4871df8b870193b5bc07eece15c03860c06.

Co-Authored-By: Matt Riedemann <mriedem.os@gmail.com>

Closes-Bug: #1793255
Related-Bug: #1798188

Change-Id: Ied268da9e70bd2807c2dfe7a479181fbec52979d

commit_message:
ceph-client: device_class support

ceph-client will apply the desired device_class to the
desired nodes. Thus user can create crush rule and pool
for their specific hardware and needs

(12 comments)

Old driver should be deprecated if just removing it, but if this is a compatible rename there should be a mapping added to the manager to https://github.com/openstack/cinder/blob/b082ae0b0574abb5feeca19676ce9d63118bedb2/cinder/volume/manager.py#L162

Since there are very significant changes with this driver, it appears it would be better to mark that old one as deprecated and remove it in the T release. That can be/should be done as part of a different patch.

This appears to switch from a fully open source driver to one that uses a proprietary library. Can you give a quick overview on the plan for third party CI?

Make sure you run tox locally before pushing up patches to make sure you've addressed at pep8 and test issues."}, {'account_id': 28940, 'date': '2018-12-10 23:12:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

 > plan for third party CI?

  The LINSTOR package is fully open source as well.  I am finalizing the in-house CI setup.  Working hard to getting that done.

My apologies.  I did run them locally, and even more thoroughly this time but obviously I'm missing something.  

I'm a bit confused on the 'cinder/opts.py' specifically after I ran 'tox genopts' to update it per Rajat's suggestion.  The new one contained both information about drbdmanagedrv (old one) and linstordrv (new one).  

After that, pep8, fast8, py27, py26, smoke, functional, and compliance all passed locally.

On the last patch 3, however, I did edit out references to the old 'drbdmangedrv' in opts.py as I was removing it from the patch.  And I'm wondering if this is where my mistake lies?

Also, if I will have to submit a separate patch for deprecation, should I keep the original drbdmanagedrv in this patch first and try to deprecate afterwards?  Thank you."}, {'account_id': 24863, 'date': '2018-12-12 19:38:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Add new LINSTOR volume driver

LINSTOR is a storage orchestrator for DRBD.

Change-Id: Ic3a4f85c10a2432d4128fce08604e9868722e8f7

commit_message:
Switch ovb_repo_version to the new branch stable/1.0

This will allow ovb to develop the new dev-2.0 version as master and
continue supporting the stable.

Once master is no longer use by CI jobs, we can finally migrate the
repository via https://review.openstack.org/#/c/620613/

This setup matches the branch naming pattern used by other openstack
projects.

Change-Id: I8e9199d59d512202842e8fa11d258c1f97549325
Story: https://tree.taiga.io/project/tripleo-ci-board/task/527

commit_message:
Fix for not released thread in get_session_client

The thread that is created in the 'network_adapter' is never released,
we should use task_manager.stop() to release unnecessary resources.
If not released each connection to service will create a threadpool
that is not detected by the garbage collector.

Change-Id: Iefb2fc55caf38eed5f79aec3622c21e80be5936b
Story: 28885

commit_message:
Improve RBAC policies panel

This is a follow-up patch of https://review.openstack.org/#/c/627741/

Create RBAC policy form:
* Merge "Action" and "Object Type" choices into a single drop-down menu.
  There is a constraint between an object type and an action and
  "access_as_external" is not a valid action for "qos_policy" object type.
  It sounds reasonable to merge "action" and "object type" into a single
  list to avoid confusion.
* Add "Select a Network" and "Select a QoS policy" to the choices of
  a target network and a target QoS policy.

Edit RBAC policy form:
* Add "*" (all projects) to "Target Project".

Part of blueprint rbac-policies
Change-Id: I135b5e5b0d4a0d8f55830ac649171e6e350db3ba

commit_message:
Only implement policy.json if an override is configured

With I23c934d2b610a451d6ebbd4276721c455365cedc merged there
is no longer a default policy.json file in the venv, so we
need to change how we implement the file, and should only do
so if there is a config override configured for it.

If there is no policy override configured, but a policy.json
file is present, then it's likely left over from a previous
build. To ensure that we do not carry legacy configuration
files which override the policy-in-code we remove the legacy
file. This is done on restart to ensure that the policy still
applies until the code is updated.

Change-Id: Ib7d8039513bc2581cf7bc0e2e73aa8ab5da82235
(cherry picked from commit d31aed7824c0c54922161db942f7b591602bfa4c)

This commit adds playbooks and roles to the ops tooling setup to
build, deploy, and operate environments with skydive within in
it.

Skydive is a network analyzer which will allow users to explore
their topology in real-time using a defined storage back-end for
captures, alerts, and more.

The initial implementation of skydive deploys agents throughout
the environment and wires them all back to a cluster of analyzers
which leverage elasticsearch for its persistent storage back-end.
Storage back-ends are load balanced from the within the analyzer
nodes using the traefik light-weight reverse proxy. This setup
gives skydive a fully fault tolerant deployment.

Tests have been added to ensure the binary installation process
is validated. While these jobs are non-voting today, they'll be
iterated on and made passing in the subsequent PRs. All jobs are
following the selective pattern which allows these tools to be
gated in the mono-repo without impacting all other tools within
the environment.

Change-Id: Iaa1152566f2b615d67a33dc94ebdbebb1b492a9d

commit_message:
Initial commit to add skydive

This commit adds playbooks and roles to the ops tooling setup to
build, deploy, and operate environments with skydive within in
it.

Skydive is a network analyzer which will allow users to explore
their topology in real-time using a defined storage back-end for
captures, alerts, and more.

The initial implementation of skydive deploys agents throughout
the environment and wires them all back to a cluster of analyzers
which leverage elasticsearch for its persistent storage back-end.
Storage back-ends are load balanced from the within the analyzer
nodes using the traefik light-weight reverse proxy. This setup
gives skydive a fully fault tolerant deployment.

Tests have been added to ensure the binary installation process
is validated. While these jobs are non-voting today, they'll be
iterated on and made passing in the subsequent PRs. All jobs are
following the selective pattern which allows these tools to be
gated in the mono-repo without impacting all other tools within
the environment.

Change-Id: Iaa1152566f2b615d67a33dc94ebdbebb1b492a9d
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin@cloudnull.com>

commit_message:
Ensure image metadata when unshelving BFV instance

When unshelving an instance that was booted from a volume,
"shelved_image_id" is None. Therefore, when performing unshelve,
the image metadata could not be retrieved and ImagePropertiesFilter
scheduling will fail.

This patch ensures image metadata is added for BFV instances by
querying the system metadata to recreate the image metadata.

Change-Id: I4ecf4f1cb51dde58c40433fae26fd17ff02807f3
Closes-Bug: #1537434
Co-Authored-By: Xiaowei Qian <xiaowei.qian@easystack.cn>
Co-Authored-By: Jay Pipes <jaypipes@gmail.com>
Co-Authored-By: Sivasathurappan Radhakrishnan <siva.radhakrishnan@intel.com>

revisions:
[{'created': '2018-12-06 16:30:08.000000000', 'message': "Fix get_location for opts in groups

get_location defines the type of its ``group`` parameter as a str,
but it then passes that directly into _do_get, which expects an
OptGroup for its parameter. When it tries to reference group.name
it blows up because a str doesn't have a .name attr.

In the interest of not changing either API, this change coerces the
group str into an OptGroup.

Closes-Bug: 1807230
Change-Id: Iae547cbd63059fa19691a7f7fe398b148effd177
"}]
commit_message:
Fix get_location for opts in groups

get_location defines the type of its ``group`` parameter as a str,
but it then passes that directly into _do_get, which expects an
OptGroup for its parameter. When it tries to reference group.name
it blows up because a str doesn't have a .name attr.

In the interest of not changing either API, this change coerces the
group str into an OptGroup.

Closes-Bug: 1807230
Change-Id: Iae547cbd63059fa19691a7f7fe398b148effd177

commit_message:
Chrony: make ntp server options configurable

Users may wish to remove the 'offline' option for increased
reliability, since ifup/ifdown scripts are typically not
required in (static) server environments. Futhermore it
enables users to adjust the polling timers to their needs.

Change-Id: Iafa31c03e98785a574f38bb2206b9bea9550743e
(cherry picked from commit cca2800ea453fba61edece248812e243f761a286)

commit_message:
Add neutron trunk utility to add ausbports to existing trunk

This patch adds a utility function to attach subports to existing trunk.
The idea is to write nova boot scenarios in future with subports being
added to trunk after booting the vm.

Change-Id: Idb3f6f2ac3a104f3ab47366f449fcc5ceb4d122f

commit_message:
Chrony: make ntp server options configurable

Users may wish to remove the 'offline' option for increased
reliability, since ifup/ifdown scripts are typically not
required in (static) server environments. Futhermore it
enables users to adjust the polling timers to their needs.

Change-Id: Iafa31c03e98785a574f38bb2206b9bea9550743e
(cherry picked from commit cca2800ea453fba61edece248812e243f761a286)

commit_message:
Remove default role-name from merge network param script

The merge-new-params-nic-config-script.py previosly had the
'Controller' role as the default for --role-name. It is not
obvious that this parameter must be changed when merging
nic config templates.

Remove the default and make the argument required. Improves
UX since user error is less likely.

Making the mistake of using a Role with too many networks
is'nt as forgiving since we now only pass parameters for
the role.networks.

Related-Bug: #1800811

commit_message:
Fix ssh agent handling of keys

A) When using ssh-agent there is no ~/.ssh/id_rsa file so the line
below will fail:

ansible_private_key_file: "~/.ssh/id_rsa"

Not mentioning the key file would allow Ansible to use the agent one.

B) fix bug where failure to dump agent key was ignore because
ssh-add -L returns 0, even when there are no keys. Now we check that
the dumped file is non-zero.

C) avoids potential failure to connect to the agent when become is
true (inhered). Avoids:

Could not open a connection to your authentication agent.

Change-Id: Ifb6454fe49339e54b2083d92b4c3800a59e01a46

When a paunch command (e.g. 'paunch list') requires inspection
of a container, it passes the container id to inspect, so we
cannot check for image availability at this time (we probably
don't need to anyway because the container exists).

commit_message:
podman: only check image availability when inspecting image

When a paunch command (e.g. 'paunch list') requires inspection
of a container, it passes the container id to inspect, so we
cannot check for image availability at this time (we probably
don't need to anyway because the container exists).

Only check for image availability if the inspect function is
requested to inspect an image.

Change-Id: I8491eddaae172c8cf0b386d4731ab72dc113049c

commit_message:
Use kafka extras for oslo.messaging

oslo.messaging replaced kafka-python to confluent-kafka [1], so instead of
adding the kafka-python to test-requirements the oslo-messaging[kafka]
should be used.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/oslo.messaging/blob/master/releasenotes/notes/kafka-client-library-change-fe16d5a34550db7f.yaml#L11

Closes-Bug: #1808350

Conflicts:

commit_message:
Update regions tests to work w/ pre-prov

I don't see any limitations by using pre-provisioned
credentials for this test:

* test_list_regions_filter_by_parent_region_id
* test_create_region_with_specific_id
* test_create_update_get_delete_region
* test_list_regions

By setting force_tenant_isolation=False this test can now
be executed with backends that don't allow user creation
(immutable user source) like LDAP.

Change-Id: Ifad293dddb7c7fe76005761b43e1252e40ce7bdc

commit_message:
Use kolla-ansible version to tag images

If building images, kolla currently uses its own version for their tag
by default.  This might not match the version of kolla-ansible, which is
what is used by default in kolla-ansible. This leads to the image not
being found.

This change uses kolla-ansible's version to tag locally built images.

Change-Id: I49c7afb9167d1e3f8a4470b6ebbb6ad6798d4996

commit_message:
kuryr: use internal neutron endpoint

Kuryr-neutron communication should use internal endpoint because
public endpoint might be protected by SSL which fails the API call.

Change-Id: I3f98f14d4f481c17a4368cc5c2a184323c548193
Closes-Bug: #1811262

commit_message:
Use kafka extras for oslo.messaging

oslo.messaging replaced kafka-python to confluent-kafka [1], so instead of
adding the kafka-python to test-requirements the oslo-messaging[kafka]
should be used.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/oslo.messaging/blob/master/releasenotes/notes/kafka-client-library-change-fe16d5a34550db7f.yaml#L11

Closes-Bug: #1808350

Conflicts:
    test-requirements.txt

Change-Id: If56890b35bbe40141c01467e47bccdf4d5584e86
(cherry picked from commit 87611fe375857990fbb084619a7ef91be39bdc03)
(cherry picked from commit 9c9110278a9521dc821b80e6c4c23bc6d01b6cf9)

commit_message:
Use correct variable for default certificate paths

The variable {{ node_config_directory }} is used for the configuration
directory on the remote hosts, and should not be used for paths on the
deploy host (localhost).

This changes the default value of the TLS certificate and CA file to
reference {{ CONFIG_DIR }}, in line with the directory used for
admin-openrc.sh (as of I0709482ead4b7a67e82796e17f85bde151e71bc0).

This change also introduces a variable, {{ node_config }}, that
references {{ CONFIG_DIR | default('/etc/kolla') }}, to remove
duplication.

Change-Id: Ibd82ac78630ebfff5824c329d7399e1e900c0ee0
Closes-Bug: #1804025

commit_message:
Don't validate .placeholder

When creating a new election we need to add a directory per project
(including the 'TC' as a pseudo project) we can't just create an empty
directory in git so we add a '.placeholder' file.

We have recently added a voting job that will run try to validate all
candidate files added in a review.  This includes the placeholder file.
CLearly this file will not pass validation and cause the job to fail.

Adding .placeholder to the zuul irrelevant-files variable wont work, so
instead filter .placeholder from the interesting files.

Change-Id: Ibd2224a5479d4ab9afbac227bac38080359a98bf

commit_message:
Handle the case when the gap between summit and release is small

Typically we have long enough post release to conduct an entire TC
election.  However with Train (and possibly others) the gap between
release and summit is too short to allow for that.  The current code
will set the eligibility criteria to allow for the release date meaning
that it's possibly for for electorate to change post-election which is a
bad thing.

Let's detect that and set the timeframe to a more logical value.

Before:
  Setting TC Election
  Summit is at: 2019-04-22
  Latest possible completion is at: 2019-03-11
  Moving back to Tuesday: 2019-03-05
  TC Election from 2019-02-26T23:45 to 2019-03-05T23:45
  TC Campaigning from 2019-02-19T23:45 to 2019-02-26T23:45
  TC Nominations from 2019-02-12T23:45 to 2019-02-19T23:45
  Set email_deadline to 2019-02-19T00:00
* Setting TC timeframe end to stein Release date 2019-04-10T00:00
  Begining of Rocky Cycle @ 2018-02-09 00:00:00+00:00
* End of Stein cycle @ 2019-04-10 00:00:00+00:00
* Election timeframe: 425 days, 0:00:00s
* Looks like election timespan is outside of 'normal'
* Minimum: 334 days, 14:00:00
* Current: 425 days, 0:00:00
* Maximum: 395 days, 10:00:00

After:
  Setting TC Election
  Summit is at: 2019-04-22
  Latest possible completion is at: 2019-03-11
  Moving back to Tuesday: 2019-03-05
  TC Election from 2019-02-26T23:45 to 2019-03-05T23:45
  TC Campaigning from 2019-02-19T23:45 to 2019-02-26T23:45
  TC Nominations from 2019-02-12T23:45 to 2019-02-19T23:45
  Set email_deadline to 2019-02-19T00:00
* Setting TC timeframe end to email_deadline
  Begining of Rocky Cycle @ 2018-02-09 00:00:00+00:00
* End of Stein cycle @ 2019-02-19 00:00:00+00:00
* Election timeframe: 375 days, 0:00:00s

Change-Id: I2ca38ea68cd179659a53a4bebe68215d91865e67

commit_message:
Fix grafana repo

Grafana repository is moved from packagecloud to
packages.grafana.com[0]. Based on new grafana install guide[1], update
the grafana.repo

[0] https://grafana.com/blog/2019/01/05/moving-to-packages.grafana.com/
[1] http://docs.grafana.org/installation/rpm/#install-via-yum-repository

Closes-Bug: #1810867
Change-Id: Ib065fdc561b72fc013b952b3df41ee83b083194e
Depends-On: https://review.openstack.org/629560
(cherry picked from commit ae883440255b02478bc3bd5cdcaf23a26869c5f1)
